To prevent HTTP Header Injection in your code, you can implement the following measures:

1. Use Framework libraries: One of the best ways to prevent HTTP Header Injection is to use framework libraries such as ASP.NET. They often have built-in protections against popular attacks like HTTP Header Injection.

2. Input validation: Ensure that all user inputs are validated before being used in the application. Regular expression filters and input masks can be used to prevent injection attacks.

3. Sanitization of user inputs: Remove special characters, white spaces, or any other unwanted characters from user input to guard against malicious attacks.

4. Security headers: Implement proper use of security headers to prevent injection attacks. For example, the X-XSS-Protection header can help protect against cross-site scripting attacks.

5. Use parameterized queries with Prepared Statements or Stored Procedures, and avoid concatenating queries in SQL strings.

6. Use HTTPOnly and Secure cookie flags: Ensuring that cookies are set with the HttpOnly and Secure flags make them resistant to client-side attacks.

7. Limit, sanitize, and validate user input before using it in HTTP headers: Always limit the length of user input and perform strict input validation before placing it in HTTP headers.

Here is an example of how to prevent HTTP Header Injection using input validation in C#:

```
string input = Request.Headers["User-Agent"];
if(!String.IsNullOrEmpty(input) && Regex.IsMatch(input, @"^[a-zA-Z0-9]*$")){
    //use input in code
}
else{
    //throw error
}
```

This code checks if the User-Agent input, retrieved from the HTTP header, contains only alphanumeric characters. If not, the input is rejected and an error is thrown.

Implementing the above measures can help prevent HTTP Header Injection attacks. It is essential to stay up to date with the latest security standards and keep your code patched with regular updates.
